Cut the @onion{1} in half through the root. Peel and chop into ½cm pieces. Cut the @echalion shallot{1} in half, peel, and chop into ½cm pieces, or even smaller if you can! Cut the top and bottom off the @courgette{2} and then slice in half lengthways. Cut each half into four strips, then chop the strips into 1cm chunks. Remove the core from the @yellow pepper{1}, then cut into thin ½cm wide slices. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{} if you have one). Pull the @mint{1} leaves off their stalks and finely chop them (discard the stalks). Roughly chop the @flat leaf parsley{1}.

Preheat your #oven{} to 180 degrees. Put the @lamb mince{500%g} in a #bowl{} and add your shallot, half your mint and the @tandoori masala spice{1.5%tsp}. Add a good pinch of @salt{pinch} and a grind of @black pepper{grind} and mix together with your hands. Divide into two balls per person, then mould into sausage shapes. Lightly flatten your sausage shapes, then thread a skewer through the middle (see picture), these are your lamb koftas! Pop your koftas on a lightly oiled #baking tray{}.

Add a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} to a large #saucepan{} on medium heat along with your onion. Cook for ~{5%minutes} until soft, then add your courgette and pepper. Season with a pinch of @salt{pinch} and a grind of @black pepper{grind} and cook for ~{5%minutes} until slightly softened. Add your garlic and @curry powder mix{1} to the pan, cook for ~{1%minute}, then add the @basmati rice{350%g} and stir together. Pour in the @coconut milk{400%ml} and @water{300%ml}, and add the @cinnamon stick{1} and @chicken stock pot{1}.

Bring to a simmer, then reduce the heat to low, pop the lid on the pan and cook for ~{10%minutes}. After 10 mins, remove the pan from the heat, take out your cinnamon stick, and pop the @baby spinach{1} on top of your rice. Put the lid back on and leave your rice to cook in its own steam for another ~{10%minutes}.

Meanwhile, put your lamb koftas on the top shelf of your oven for ~{20%minutes}. Turn them over halfway through.

> The lamb is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle.

While your rice and lamb cook, put the @Greek style natural yoghurt{1} in a bowl with your remaining mint, a small pinch of @salt{pinch} and a grind of @black pepper{grind}. Mix together.

Get your washing up done and put your feet up for ~{5%minutes}!

Add half your parsley to your rice and stir well, making sure your spinach is mixed through too. Serve your rice in bowls with your lamb koftas on top and a dollop of minty yoghurt. Sprinkle over your remaining parsley and enjoy!